		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../atem.png" alt="ATEM 2006 SI"></a><br><code>atem2006s/paper01</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Extending Grammars and Metamodels for Reuse: the Reuseware Approach</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JakobHenriksson.html">Jakob Henriksson</a>, <a href="../profile/FlorianHeidenreich.html">Florian Heidenreich</a>, <a href="../profile/JendrikJohannes.html">Jendrik Johannes</a>, <a href="../profile/SteffenZschaler.html">Steffen Zschaler</a>, <a href="../profile/UweAßmann.html">Uwe Aßmann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1049/iet-sen:20070060">10.1049/iet-sen:20070060</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="https://devboost.github.io/Reuseware/CoCoNut/org.reuseware.coconut/publications/2007_WCOP_Reuseware.pdf"><em>How Dark Should a Component Black-Box Be? The Reuseware Answer (WCOP 2007)</em></a> &amp; <a href="https://www.jot.fm/issues/issue_2007_10/paper7.pdf"><em>Reuseware – Adding Modularity to Your Language of Choice (TOOLS 2007)</em></a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagM">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes language-independent mechanisms to enable reusable, composable partial programs as a systematic reuse feature for DSLs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It introduces composition constructs and a composition process to assemble encapsulated language components into complete programs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It presents the Reuseware Composition Framework as tool support for implementing the proposed reuse/composition approach.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It operates on grammars and metamodels as language definition artefacts that are extended to support reuse.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
	</body>
</html>
